  "title": "Optimizing Command Line Interface (CLI) Tools Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to leverage FastAPI, a modern, fast (high-performance), web framework for building APIs, to optimize CLI tools in Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI provides both HTTP and non-HTTP entry points for easy conversion of existing CLIs into FastAPI applications.",
    "It supports automatic generation of client code, making it easier to consume your API from a CLI.",
    "FastAPI can handle concurrent requests efficiently, improving the performance of your CLI tool.",
    "Error handling and validation are built-in, ensuring robustness and usability."
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI\napp = FastAPI()\ndef my_function():\n    ...\n@app.get('/my_endpoint')\ndef my_function_fastapi():\n    ...\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    my_function() # replace with your existing CLI code\n    uvicorn main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python version: 3.12+"
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "FastAPI requires additional dependencies such as uvicorn and Pyronia.",
    "While FastAPI can improve performance, it may add some overhead compared to traditional CLIs.",
    "Proper configuration is necessary for optimal results."
  ]
}

